  "text": "Random walks is a mathematical model of a random process, which leads an unlabeled element to a labeled seed with the highest likelihood [CITATION_1] . Given a graph structure G = (V, E) with nodes v ∈ V and edges e ∈ E, the task of random walks is to group the nodes into K classes. Assume that the elements set is given as X = {x 1 , . . . , x N } ∈ R m , where N is the number of elements. The connection between any two nodes x u and x v in X (i.e., the weight of the edge w uv ) is quantified by a weight matrix W = [w uv ] N×N . Here, we assume that the connection between any two nodes is undirected (i.e., w uv = w vu ) [CITATION_2] and w uv is empirically obtained by the typical Gaussian weighting function:",
